title: For Sale:  640 Rds Yugo M67 7.62x39 Brass Case
location: Fuquay Varina, Raleigh / Durham / CH, North Carolina
postcontent:
FS: 640 Rounds of Yugo M67 7.62x39 ammo. Fresh from a spam can repacked in a .50 cal ammo can. Packed 40 rds to the box on 10 rd stripper clips. Fuquay Varina, NC.   Last couple cans.  When they're gona that's it.  $190
There is plenty of 7.62x39 ammo on the market, but most of it is best used for practice and plinking on the range. Most 7.62x39 including HPs doesn't expand very well and isn't good SHTF/Self-Defense ammo. The Yugo M67 is an exception though and is some of the last true military surplus 7.62x39 ammo on the market.
The Yugo M67 bullet was designed to produce a superior wounding profile, speed, and accuracy. If you are looking for the best surplus 7.62x39 Ammunition for your AK then the Yugo is one of the best choices because it is true mil-spec, sealed primer and projectile, annealed brass case, and just a tad hotter of a load than the typical steel case options. Ammo is berdan primed for a long shelf life. It is mildly corrosive having corrosive properties in the primer which require clean up after shooting but those same properties extend the shelf life and sure fire capabilities even longer.
(This pic is of some other Yugo 7.62 ammo I had. The pic below is of the same ammo but loose in 15 rd boxes instead of stripper clips. This listing is identical only 640 rds in 40 rd boxes on stripper clips.)

title: For Sale:  Adams Arms Piston AR15 plus Extras
location: South Tally, Will Travel, Tallahassee, Florida
postcontent: PRICE DROP--NEED GONEI have decided to list my Adams Arms AR-15. It is a piston driven AR, which yields a lot of great benefits, in that it cycles faster, runs cleaner, cooler, and more reliably, and is easier to take down and clean. If you have questions about the Piston vs. the standard Direct Impingement system, I encourage you to look it up. The Truth About Guns did a review on this gun, and it can be found at this link:http://www.thetruthaboutguns.com/2014/03/foghorn/gun-review-adams-arms-tactical-evo-rifle/The current version of this rifle can be found online at the adams arms website, though it is severely backordered:http://www.adamsarms.net/16-mid-tactical-evo-rifleThe lower is a Spartan Tactical "MOLON LABE" lower which has been colorized in Red and White. This stripped lower can be found at:http://www.joeboboutfitters.com/Spartan_15_Enhanced_Billet_Lower_Receiver_p/jb-spartan15.htmI am willing to include a lot of the accessories which I have for this rifle. Too many to list, but if you have any questions please don't hesitate to ask me. (NOTE: There are a few things that are in the pic that I no longer have)There is a 3-9x40mm scope mounted on the gun in the pics, with parallax adjustment and illuminated reticle. It can put 5-shot groups in 2 MOA at 100 yds all day (with several sub-MOA groups mixed in)--and I haven't sandbagged it or put it in a vise or anything, that's just shooting from the grip pod (and I'm a crappy shot!). I also have a 4-reticle reflex sight with an optionally attached laser and a pressure pad. (The scope is not on the gun right now, but I can include it if desired.  Currently has the reflex sight)I have a grip-pod on this gun, as seen in the attached photos(those things aren't cheap...).  5 magazines--2x Magpul Gen3 window mags(awesome), 1x tapco AR15 Mag, and 2x steel mags. All work perfect.I currently have 840 rounds of brass cased 5.56 ammo (including 70 rounds of hollow point) to include with the deal. I can also include only 340 rounds if you would like, or zero.This gun has been meticulously taken care of and cleaned after every trip to the range. If you are a serious buyer, I would be happy to show you how to take it all the way down with the piston system--it's not difficult. I firmly believe that this is one of the nicest AR-15s I have ever shot, and it continually impresses me. I can honestly say that I have never had a misfire with it. I am just at a point in my life where this gun doesn't make a ton of sense for me to own. It's a great firearm and I would love to see it go to somebody who will use it and enjoy it.As always, cash talks, but I would also be interested in a trade for other firearms, or really anything of interest. I would consider any rifles, pistols, or shotguns, bows, hunting/target/defense, anything. If you only want some of this stuff, you can make an offer on just part of it.  We can also work out a trade plus cash, whatever it takes. Worst I can say is no, so make an offer!Thanks for looking.

postcontent: You are looking at a truly rare and special fire arm.  Based on the coveted Weatherby Mark V action, originally chamberd in .460 Magnum, this masculine rifle was rebarreled in the even more potent chambering  of .510 Wells Express!  This is a wildcat of the massive .460 Weatherby invented by the late and renouned gunsmith Fred Wells of Prescott Arizona.  It chamber is nearly identical to the .500 A-Square, only a little more refined.  This action is the very desireable Southgate vintage, as those were all manufactured in Japan.  I do not know the complete history of this rifle, as I am not the original owner, but understand it has seen time in the bush, however if it was bloodied I do not know.  The stock is obviously custom in XXX fancy Claro walnut, the action is nicely cross bolted, the bolt is jeweled and the handle is spoon-cut with an in-laid red ruby, standard safari stype iron sights, pistol grip has an in-laid golden Gizzly bear head, metal is finished in traditional plumb-brown...etc..  This is a finely detailed, very solid, ultra-powerful custom rifle - yes this is the real deal.  With only 65 rounds done its 25" barrel, yes it is nearly new.  Condition is grade - "NRA excellent".  Bore is grade 9 on a 1-10 scale, due to the familiar surface frosting in the grooves at the muzzle so common with safari rifles.  This is very minor, purely cosmetic having zero impact on strength or accuracy.  I've had this in my collection for over 15 years, have enjoyed owning it emmensly, but it's time for a new shooter and care taker.  Includes everything pictured: rifle, reloading dies, neck expander die (gently expands .460" to .510"), Brass - new & once fired, and a total of 129 Bullets which are solids and jacketed (500, 600, and 700 grain).  I look forward to hearing from you so I can share much more detail, reload recipes, and answer whatever questions you may have.
